---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";
import CodeTabs from "../../../components/CodeTabs.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Monitoring & Observability">
  <h1>Monitoring &amp; Observability</h1>
  <p>
    EntDB ships with first-class hooks for the four pillars operators
    actually need: a health RPC for orchestrators, Prometheus metrics for
    dashboards, OpenTelemetry traces for request flows, and structured
    logs for audit and debugging. Everything is opt-in via environment
    variables and degrades gracefully if a dependency is missing.
  </p>

  <h2>Health Checks</h2>
  <p>
    The server exposes a <code>Health</code> gRPC method on the main
    listener (default <code>0.0.0.0:50051</code>). It returns the
    aggregated status of the WAL connection and the local storage layer,
    plus per-component detail you can scrape into a dashboard.
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`from entdb_sdk import Client

client = Client(target="entdb:50051")
await client.connect()

status = await client.health(timeout=2.0)
# {"healthy": True, "version": "1.0.0",
#  "components": {"wal": "healthy", "storage": "healthy"}}`}
    goNote="Health is exposed on the underlying gRPC connection. Until a typed Go helper lands, call HealthRequest{} directly via the generated stub or hit the port with grpcurl from your liveness probe sidecar."
  />

  <p>
    Wire the same RPC to Kubernetes liveness and readiness probes via
    <code>grpc-health-probe</code>:
  </p>
  <Code code={`livenessProbe:
  exec:
    command: ["/bin/grpc_health_probe", "-addr=:50051"]
  initialDelaySeconds: 10
  periodSeconds: 10
readinessProbe:
  exec:
    command: ["/bin/grpc_health_probe", "-addr=:50051"]
  initialDelaySeconds: 2
  periodSeconds: 5`} lang="yaml" />

  <p>
    The server only flips its internal <code>_running</code> flag after
    the WAL connection succeeds, so readiness will fail until the WAL is
    reachable. This is the desired behaviour &mdash; do not promote a
    pod that cannot append events.
  </p>

  <h2>Prometheus Metrics</h2>
  <p>
    Set <code>METRICS_ENABLED=true</code> (default in production images)
    and the server starts a Prometheus exposition endpoint on
    <code>METRICS_PORT</code> (default <code>9090</code>) at the standard
    <code>/metrics</code> path.
  </p>
  <Code code={`METRICS_ENABLED=true
METRICS_PORT=9090`} lang="bash" />

  <h3>Exported Metrics</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Labels</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_grpc_requests_total</code></td><td>counter</td><td>method, status</td><td>Total gRPC requests by method and outcome.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_grpc_latency_seconds</code></td><td>histogram</td><td>method</td><td>Per-method request latency (1ms&ndash;5s buckets).</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_applier_events_total</code></td><td>counter</td><td>status</td><td>Events the applier processed (<code>applied</code>, <code>skipped</code>, <code>error</code>).</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_applier_lag_seconds</code></td><td>gauge</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>How far the applier is behind the WAL head.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_wal_appends_total</code></td><td>counter</td><td>status</td><td>WAL append attempts.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_wal_append_latency_seconds</code></td><td>histogram</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>WAL append latency (1ms&ndash;1s buckets).</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_sqlite_operations_total</code></td><td>counter</td><td>operation</td><td>SQLite read/write counts.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>entdb_active_tenants</code></td><td>gauge</td><td>&mdash;</td><td>Number of tenants with open SQLite handles.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>Useful PromQL</h3>
  <Code code={`# p99 request latency per method
histogram_quantile(0.99,
  sum by (method, le) (rate(entdb_grpc_latency_seconds_bucket[5m])))

# Error rate (per method)
sum by (method) (rate(entdb_grpc_requests_total{status="error"}[5m]))
  / sum by (method) (rate(entdb_grpc_requests_total[5m]))

# Applier lag — alert if > 30s for 5m
max(entdb_applier_lag_seconds) > 30

# WAL append p99
histogram_quantile(0.99,
  sum by (le) (rate(entdb_wal_append_latency_seconds_bucket[5m])))`} lang="promql" />

  <h3>Scrape Configuration</h3>
  <Code code={`scrape_configs:
  - job_name: entdb
    metrics_path: /metrics
    kubernetes_sd_configs:
      - role: pod
    relabel_configs:
      - source_labels: [__meta_kubernetes_pod_label_app]
        action: keep
        regex: entdb
      - source_labels: [__meta_kubernetes_pod_container_port_number]
        action: keep
        regex: "9090"`} lang="yaml" />

  <h2>Distributed Tracing</h2>
  <p>
    Tracing is OpenTelemetry-based and ships spans over OTLP/gRPC. Enable
    it with three environment variables; the server applies the sampler
    at startup, so changes require a restart.
  </p>
  <Code code={`TRACE_ENABLED=true
TRACE_EXPORTER=otlp           # console, otlp
TRACE_ENDPOINT=http://otel-collector:4317
TRACE_SAMPLING_RATE=0.1        # 10% head-based sampling`} lang="bash" />

  <p>
    Spans are emitted around gRPC handlers, WAL appends, and SQLite
    operations. Send the OTLP stream to any collector &mdash; Jaeger,
    Tempo, Datadog Agent &mdash; that speaks OTLP/gRPC on port 4317. To
    debug locally without a collector, set
    <code>TRACE_EXPORTER=console</code> and spans print to stdout.
  </p>

  <h2>Structured Logging</h2>
  <p>
    Logs default to JSON for production, with one record per event. Use
    text for local development.
  </p>
  <Code code={`LOG_LEVEL=INFO     # DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR
LOG_FORMAT=json    # json or text`} lang="bash" />

  <p>
    The JSON formatter emits <code>time</code>, <code>level</code>,
    <code>logger</code>, <code>message</code>, plus any structured
    <code>extra</code> fields the call site supplied (tenant_id, actor,
    stream_pos, latency_ms). Library noise from <code>aiokafka</code>
    and <code>botocore</code> is pinned to <code>WARNING</code> so the
    signal-to-noise ratio stays high.
  </p>

  <h2>gRPC Reflection</h2>
  <p>
    Reflection is on by default (<code>GRPC_REFLECTION=true</code>) so
    operators can introspect the running service with
    <code>grpcurl</code>. Disable it on internet-exposed deployments
    &mdash; it leaks every method name and message schema to anyone who
    can reach the port.
  </p>
  <Code code={`# List services
grpcurl -plaintext entdb:50051 list

# Inspect a method
grpcurl -plaintext entdb:50051 describe entdb.v1.EntDB.Health

# Call Health
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{}' entdb:50051 entdb.v1.EntDB/Health`} lang="bash" />

  <Code code={`# Production: turn it off
GRPC_REFLECTION=false`} lang="bash" />

  <h2>Suggested SLOs</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>SLI</th><th>Target</th><th>Burn-rate alert</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Request availability (non-error / total)</td><td>99.9% monthly</td><td>2% error budget over 1h</td></tr>
    <tr><td>p99 request latency</td><td>&lt; 100ms (read), &lt; 250ms (write)</td><td>3x target for 10m</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Applier lag</td><td>&lt; 5s p95</td><td>&gt; 30s for 5m (page)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>WAL append p99</td><td>&lt; 50ms</td><td>&gt; 200ms for 5m</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Snapshot freshness</td><td>&le; snapshot interval + 10%</td><td>2x interval (page)</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>Recommended Dashboard Panels</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Throughput</strong>: <code>sum by (method) (rate(entdb_grpc_requests_total[1m]))</code></li>
    <li><strong>Latency heatmap</strong>: <code>sum by (le) (rate(entdb_grpc_latency_seconds_bucket[1m]))</code></li>
    <li><strong>Applier health</strong>: <code>entdb_applier_lag_seconds</code> with annotated deploys</li>
    <li><strong>WAL pipeline</strong>: <code>rate(entdb_wal_appends_total&lbrace;status="ok"&rbrace;[1m])</code> vs <code>rate(entdb_applier_events_total&lbrace;status="applied"&rbrace;[1m])</code></li>
    <li><strong>Tenants</strong>: <code>entdb_active_tenants</code> (capacity planning)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/tenant-shard-db/docs/deploy/wal">WAL Backends</a></li>
